english:
  title: Record of the Shrine to Commemorate Administrator Sin Tam
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: "Yeongsan has been a county for ages. During Silla it was called Seohwa and Sangyak; during Goryeo it became Yeongsan, as it remains today. My maternal great-grandfather, Governor of Seoul Yi, made his home there, and from that time my mother's family settled widely throughout the county. My family's ancestral lands lay in Cheongdo District, which stands but sixty li from the county—near enough that I heard much of it from people, and through ties of kinship I traveled there often, coming to know well the affairs of Yeongsan.\n\nIn the summer of 1483, Administrator Sin Tam of Goyang, serving as Director of the Military Equipment Bureau, sought the post in this county for the convenience of caring for his parents. All who spoke of him told only of his virtuous governance. That autumn, his second son sought transfer to Changnyeong to better serve their aging mother, and I myself was then teaching at Jinju. Traveling there for filial visits, I passed through the region and each time saw Administrator Sin, delighting in his gentle manner. When his term ended and he departed, I composed verses in farewell: \"The qin and the crane drift on clear winds afar, / The black-haired people keep the love he gave them long. / Though you leave this day, / Someday this place shall be your native home.\" \n\nThat same autumn, I withdrew from my post at Jinju due to illness and dwelt in Cheongdo. After morning and evening visits with my mother, I would close my gate and sit in quiet solitude, turning from the dust of the world. One day a visitor knocked, and I sent out my servant. He returned with a scholar from Yeongsan. We sat together, and he spoke thus: \"When Administrator Sin descended from his carriage, he extended his heart to the common folk with compassion and ruled with dignity. He controlled his clerks with authority yet governed with simplicity. Taxation fell evenly, punishments were just. Incorruptible yet capable, he enriched public works without burdening the people. His rule was gentle, yet his orders swiftly obeyed. He sought not the appearance of wisdom, nor the façade of purity—in all his governance, he reached the heights of perfection. Our Yeongsan soil is high and dry, bordered by a great lake yet unsuited to irrigation. When water or drought strikes, we suffer before all other counties. In the famine year of 1485, Administrator Sin went forth at dawn, visiting every household. He exhausted every means to prepare stores against hunger, carrying congee and rice, feeding the hungry as a mother nurses her child. From near and far, all who heard came to Yeongsan seeking succor. The Administrator drew upon the example of Cheongju in his relief efforts, and not a single person in our whole territory perished. Without Administrator Sin, we would long have become barren earth. Yet while all things have beginnings, few achieve completion. The Administrator's governance spanned six terms, and his ending matched his beginning. The longer he served, the more our people cherished him—not merely satisfied, but unable to bear his departure. When the time came for his transfer, all wept and begged that he remain but one more year. Yet our weak prayers, like ants before the throne, could not reach the nine-layered palace. To keep a phoenix long upon thorns would serve neither the phoenix nor the Administrator, so we resolved instead to commission his portrait and keep it in our soil, that we might revere him each spring and autumn, nursing in our hearts the affection we cannot express.\"\n\nThe elders gathered funds for a painter. Following the messenger into the magistrate's court, they watched while Administrator Sin attended to his duties, capturing his likeness without his knowledge. Upon reviewing the work, should a single hair be amiss, they would commission corrections. After a month of such refinement, the portrait achieved perfect resemblance. Once mounted on silk and properly prepared, it was kept in safekeeping. After the Administrator's departure, they resolved to build a shrine. The people came in joy, great and small contributing what they could. Even the widowed and widowers who could barely meet their daily needs spared no expense. Grain and cloth were gathered by the hundred measures, enough to purchase materials. Upon the open ground east of the magistrate's office, they built the shrine. The elders then said: \"To preserve Administrator Sin's deeds permanently in our soil, we should commission a scholar to write an inscription. We shall have someone inform the learned gentleman, and when the shrine is completed, we shall have it carved in wood to endure forever.\"\n\nI rose and bowed, saying: \"Your request does great honor to the Administrator and to his deeds, yet my brush is clumsy and insufficient to do them justice. Pray return and seek instead one of the accomplished literary masters.\" Yet I lingered, reflecting deeply, and found myself reciting those verses I had given the Administrator years before: \"Though you leave this place, / Someday this shall be your native home.\" I thought: \"The Administrator will depart, yet his spirit shall long be cherished here, as in his native Dongyang. Yet he has ordered his children to bury him there, and the people of his native place, moved by his memory, built him a shrine—such was Zhu Yi of old. Now the people of Yeongsan raise a shrine not for the Administrator himself, but from admiration of his virtue. In seeking to honor such virtue through perpetual veneration, what better way than to enshrine him while yet living? Long ago the people of Weizhou raised a shrine to Magistrate Di Lianggong while he lived—thus is the living shrine not invention of Yeongsan. The people of Yizhou commissioned a portrait of Zhang Fangping—thus Yeongsan's portrait of Administrator Sin is likewise worthy. When the people long for the Administrator yet cannot see him, they shall bow before his image and kindle their affection. In such reverent form, though the Administrator has gone, he remains. Thus I know the elders of Yeongsan are no ordinary folk.\" I offered wine and sent them off.\n\nSoon after, I received appointment as Liaison Officer to Liaodong and hurried to my post without opportunity to write the inscription. Months later, returning southward, the elders of Yeongsan sent word: \"A gentleman delights in praising the virtue of others. Though we earnestly sought an inscription before, you did not comply—not that we lacked knowledge of other capable hands, yet none knows Administrator Sin as you do, nor knows the affairs of Yeongsan as thoroughly. We beseech you most earnestly.\"\n\nI reflected: Our Lord has reigned now for twenty years, attending diligently to the welfare of the people, entrusting grave responsibilities to those who govern intimately among them—yet few truly fulfill this trust. Now Administrator Sin has distinguished himself above the ordinary, his benevolence flowing downward, seeping deep into the hearts of the people. Truly, Administrator Sin was a worthy man! The people have gathered to commission his portrait and sought a scholar to inscribe his record. The hearts of Yeongsan are indeed earnest. Officials who shepherd the people for our Lord should observe this and be moved; and the common folk should learn from it the virtue of repaying kindness.\n\nConsidering the precedents of the East: Throughout the three thousand years since the Three Kingdoms, many officials have gained renown, yet I have never heard of such a living shrine. It is in the flourishing age of our Lord that this first appears—revealing the brilliance of his wisdom, the talent of his people, and the beauty of their transformed customs.\n\nAdministrator Sin's courtesy name was Cheonggyeong. A successful candidate in the civil examination of 1492, he was by nature earnest and solemn—reticent in speech yet quick in action, fond of poetry and learned in letters. Thus his governance had deep foundations. I now record these particulars in response.\n\nSomeone later asked me: \"Administrator Sin's governance was not remarkably different from others', yet why did the people come to cherish him so deeply?\" I replied: \"Those who create distinction to appear lofty, the gentleman does not respect. True and sincere action without display of merit—this is the mark of a true administrator of the old way.\"\n\nThereafter I composed these verses:\n\nThose who gave me birth are my mother and father,\nHe who gave me life is the Administrator.\nThe Administrator's virtue rivals my very breath,\nWhile he lived and gave us sustenance,\nWhat need had we of shrines?\nNow that he has gone, our longing finds no resting place,\nHis form serves in the court,\nYet his image dwells within our hall."
  footnotes:
    - 'Yeongsan: A county in present-day South Korea.'
    - 'Silla, Goryeo: The Three Kingdoms period and subsequent dynasty referenced in Korean history.'
    - '1483 (Year Gyeongsin) and 1485 (Year Eulsaa): Specific years during the Joseon Dynasty when Administrator Sin served.'
    - 'Cheongdo and Jinju: Geographic locations in Korea relevant to the author''s own biography.'
    - 'Zhu Yi: A celebrated administrator from ancient China whose memory was honored even after death, providing precedent for the veneration described.'
    - 'Di Lianggong: Another celebrated Chinese magistrate honored with a shrine during his lifetime.'
    - 'Zhang Fangping: A Chinese official whose portrait was preserved by the people he served.'
    - 'Dongyang (Toryeong): Administrator Sin''s native region, referenced in the farewell poem.'
    - 'The ''living shrine'' (생사당): A shrine erected while the honored person yet lives, marking extraordinary popular devotion and recognition of virtue.'
